Sort Algorithms Comparison

Author: Sergio García de la Iglesia, Joaquin Sanchiz Navarro


A sort algorithm is an algorithm that inserts a list of elements into a sequence given by an order relation. The output of the algorithm will be a ordered version of the input given, that satisfy the order relation. The most common order relations are the numerical order and the lexical order. Efficient sort algorithms are important to improve other algorithms (like search algorithms and merge algorithms) that require ordered lists for a better performance.

chapter1.html.title: Sort Algorithms
chapter1.html.body:
Sort Algorithms

Types of sort algorithms
Sort algorithms can be classified by:

The place where the sort takes place:
Internal sort algorithms: in the main computer memory.
External sort algorithms: in an external place like a secondary memory.


The time the algorithm takes to compute the sort, with the input given already sorted or inversely sorted:
Natural sort algorithms: it takes the minimum possible time when the input is ordered.
Non natural sort algorithms: it takes the minimum possible time when the input is inversely ordered.


The steadiness of the algorithm:
An stable sort keeps the relative order that the elements with same keys had originally. For example: if a list sort by dates is resorted in alphabetical order with an stable sort algorithm, all of the elements with the same alphabetical key will be sorted by date. A non stable sort algorithm can be implemented to be a stable sort algorithm. One way to do that would be to modify the order key, so the relative original position on the list can participate on the sort in case of coincidence.



Characteristics

Computational complexity (best, worst and average case complexity) in terms of size n. The best sort behavior (unless you don't use the key structure) is $${O(n log n)}$$. The most simple algorithms are quadratic, $${O(n^2)}$$.
Memory usage and other computational means. Also $${O(n)}$$ notation is used.

merge-sort.html.title: Merge Sort
merge-sort.html.body:
Merge Sort

Merge sort algorithm is an external stable sort algorithm divide and conquer based. It is $${O(n log n)}$$ complex.
Conceptually, merge sort computes like this:

If the n size is 0 or 1, it is already ordered. In other case:
Divide the unordered list in two $$\frac{n}{2}$$ sublists.
Order each sublist recursively applying merge sort.
Merge both sublists in one ordered list.

Merge sort contains two main ideas to improve the running time:

A small list will need less steps to get ordered than a bigger list.
It will need less steps to build an ordered list from two ordered lists, than from two non ordered lists.

Computational cost

Dividing: $${O(1)}$$

Sorting: $${2T(\frac{n}{2})}$$

Merging: $${O(n)}$$

merge-sort-vs-insertion-sort.html.body:
Merge Sort vs Insertion Sort

As we checked before, Merge Sort is faster than Insertion sort, due to the first one is O(nlog(n)) and the second one is O(n^2).
There is an optimization for Merge Sort method, where when the sublist is less size than 7, Insertion Sort is faster, so it is applied in this case.
